<DOC><DOCNO> AP890704-0042 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-07-04-89 0439EST</FILEID><FIRST>r i PM-Bangladesh-Floods     07-04 0185</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Bangladesh-Floods,0189</SECOND><HEAD>50 Villages Hit by Floods, Two Dead</HEAD><DATELINE>DHAKA, Bangladesh (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Flash floods swept through 50 villagesand drowned at least two people after heavy rains forced tributariesof the Brahmaputra River over their banks, officials said today.   The floods began Monday in the northern and eastern regions ofthe country after monsoon rains swelled the rivers, Relief Ministryofficials said. They said at least 50 villages were flooded, andrice crops were damaged.   At least two people were washed away by rising water in theBandarban district 150 miles southeast of Dhaka, police in the areasaid.   Sangbad, a Dhaka-based newspaper, said at least 20,000 peoplewere marooned by the floods in the northern district of Rangpur. Itsaid they took refuge on high ground or roofs.   Bangladesh, a low-lying country of 110 million people, iscriss-crossed by hundreds of rivers that form the deltas of theBrahmaputra and the Ganges rivers. The summer monsoons usually causeflooding.   Last year, floods inundated about four-fifths of Bangladesh, andat least 1,400 people were killed. At least 2.3 million people wereleft homeless.</TEXT></DOC>